<h3></h3>
<div class='layout'><p>1 Mathematician</p><p>第1章 数学家</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>CLEON I:……The last Galactic Emperor of……Entun dynasty. He……born in……year 11,988 of……Galactic Era,……same year in which Hari Seldon……born.……is thought that Seldons birthdate, which some consider doubtful,……have been adjusted to match that of Cleon, whom Seldon, soon after……arrival on Trantor, is supposed to have encountered.)</p><p>克里昂一世：……银河帝国恩腾皇朝的末代皇帝。生于银河纪元11988年，亦即哈里·谢顿诞生的同一年。（有人认为谢顿的生年并不可靠，可能经过后人篡改，目的在于构成此一巧合。谢顿抵达川陀之后，想必很快便见到这位皇帝。）</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Having succeeded to……Imperial throne in 12,010 at……age of twenty-two, Cleon Is reign represented a curious interval of quiet in those troubled times. This is undoubtedly……to……skills of……Chief of Staff,……Demerzel,……so carefully obscured himself from public record that little is known about him.</p><p>银河纪元12010年，二十二岁的克里昂一世继承帝位。在那个纷扰不断的时代里，他的统治代表了一段传奇的平静岁月，这无疑得归功于行政首长伊图·丹莫刺尔的政治长才。丹莫刺尔则始终谨慎地隐迹幕后，避免留下公开记录，以致后人对他的了解极其有限。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon himself……</p><p>克里昂本人……</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>ENCYCLOPEDIA GALACTICA</p><p>……《银河百科全书》</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>(All quotations from……Encyclopedia Galactica here reproduced……taken from……116th Edition, published 1,020 FE by……Encyclopedia Galactica Publishing Co., Terminus, with permission of……publishers.)</p><p></p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Suppressing a small yawn, Cleon said, "Demerzel, have……by……chance ever heard of a……named Hari Seldon?"</p><p>压下一个小小的呵欠后，克里昂开口道：“丹莫刺尔，你会不会刚好听说过一个叫哈里·谢顿的人？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon……been Emperor……just over……years……there were times at state occasions when, dressed in……necessary robes……regalia, he could manage to look stately. He……so,……instance, in……holograph of himself that stood in……niche in……wall behind him. It……placed so that it clearly dominated……other niches holding……holographs of several of……ancestors. </p><p>克里昂继承皇位刚超过十年，在一些国家大典上，当他穿上不可或缺的皇袍，佩上象征皇室的饰物，看起来也能显得冠冕堂皇。举例而言，他身后壁凹中那尊全息立像便是如此。这尊立像显然摆在最突出的位置，令其他壁凹中几位先人的全息像相形见绌。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The holograph……not a totally honest one,……though Cleons hair……light brown in hologram……reality alike, it……a……thicker in……holograph. There……a certain asymmetry to……real face,……the left side of……upper……raised itself a……higher than……right side,……this……somehow……evident in……holograph.……if he……stood up……placed himself beside……holograph, he would have been seen to be 2 centimeters under……1.83-meter height that……image portrayed……and perhaps a……stouter. </p><p>这尊全息像并非完全写实。例如它的头发虽然也是淡褐色，看来与真实的克里昂无异，却稍嫌浓密了一点。他真正的脸庞有些不对称，上唇左边比右边高些，这点在全息像中也不怎么明显。此外，假如他站起身来，走到自己的全息像旁边，旁人便能看出他比身高一米八三的立像矮了二厘米……或许还丰满少许。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Of course,……holograph……the official coronation portrait……he……been younger then. He still looked young……rather handsome, too,……when he……not in……pitiless grip of official ceremony, there……a kind of vague good nature about……face.</p><p>当然，这个全息像是加冕典礼的正式定装照，况且当时他也比较年轻。如今，他看来年轻依旧，而且相当英俊，在没有官方礼节的无情束缚时，也会露出一种含糊的和善表情。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said, with……tone of respect that he carefully cultivated, "Hari Seldon? It is an unfamiliar name to……Sire. Ought I to know of him?"</p><p>丹莫刺尔以细心揣摩的恭敬语调说：“哈里·谢顿？启禀陛下，这个名字我并不熟悉。我应该认识他吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"The Minister of Science mentioned……to me last night. I thought……might."</p><p>“科学部长昨晚跟我提到这个人。我想你或许听说过。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel frowned slightly,……only very slightly,……one does……frown in……Imperial presence. "The Minister of Science, Sire, should have spoken of this……to me as Chief of Staff. If……are to be bombarded from every side……"</p><p>丹莫刺尔轻轻皱了皱眉头，但那只是很轻微的一蹙，因为在圣驾前不应有此举动。“陛下，科学部长若要谈及此人，应该来找身为行政首长的我。假如上上下下都对您疲劳轰炸……”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon raised……hand……Demerzel stopped at once. "Please, Demerzel,……cant stand on formality at……times. When I passed……Minister at last nights reception……exchanged a……words with him, he bubbled over. I could……refuse to listen……I……glad I had,……it……interesting."</p><p>克里昂举起手来，丹莫刺尔立刻闭嘴。“拜托，丹莫刺尔，你不能一天到晚指望别人中规中矩。昨晚的欢迎会上，我经过那位部长身边，跟他闲谈了几句，他就一发不可收拾。我无法拒绝，而我很高兴听到那番话，因为实在很有意思。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"In what……interesting, Sire?"</p><p>“怎样有意思，陛下？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well, these……not……old days when science……mathematics were……the rage. That sort of thing seems to have died down somehow, perhaps because……the discoveries have been made, don't……think? Apparently, however, interesting things……still happen. At least I……told it……interesting."</p><p>“嗯，时代变了，科学和数学不再像以往那么时兴。那些东西似乎多少已经过气，也许是因为能发现的都被发现了，你不这样想吗？然而，有意思的事显然还是不会绝迹，至少他是这么告诉我的。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"By……Minister of Science, Sire?"</p><p>“科学部长吗，陛下？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yes. He said that this Hari Seldon……attended a convention of mathematicians held here in Trantor……they do this every……years,……some reason……and he said that he……proved that……could foretell……future mathematically."</p><p>“没错，他说这个哈里·谢顿参加了一个在我们川陀举行的数学家会议……基于某种原因，这个会议每十年举行一次……他在会上声称，他已经证明人类可以利用数学预测未来。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel permitted himself a small smile. "Either……Minister of Science, a……of little acumen, is mistaken or……mathematician……Surely,……matter of foretelling……future is a childrens dream of magic."</p><p>丹莫刺尔故意露出一抹微笑。“科学部长这个人并不怎么精明，若不是他弄错了，就是这个数学家错了。不用说，预测未来这种事是小孩才会相信的把戏。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Is……Demerzel? People believe in such things."</p><p>“是吗，丹莫刺尔？民众都相信这种事情。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"People believe in many things, Sire."</p><p>“陛下，民众相信很多事情。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But they believe in such things. Therefore, it doesnt matter whether……forecast of……future is true or not. If a mathematician should predict a long……happy reign……me, a time of peace……prosperity……the Empire……Eh, would that……be well?"</p><p>“可是他们的确相信这种事情。因此之故，对未来的预测是否正确并不重要。假如一名数学家作出预测，说我能够带来长治久安，说帝国将有一段太平繁荣的岁月……啊，这难道不好吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It would be pleasant to hear, certainly,……what would it accomplish, Sire?"</p><p>“当然，这种说法听来很舒服，可是陛下，它又有什么用呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But surely if people believe this, they would……on that belief. Many a prophecy, by……mere force of……being believed, is transmuted to fact. These……self-fulfilling prophecies. Indeed,……that I think of……it……you……once explained this to me."</p><p>“只要民众深信不疑，当然就会依据这个信念而行动。许多预言最后终于成真，唯一的凭借只是信心的力量。这就是所谓的‘自我实现的预言’。没错，现在我想起来了，当初对我解释这个道理的就是你。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said, "I believe I did, Sire."……eyes were watching……Emperor carefully, as though to……how……he might go on……own. "Still, if that be……one could have……person make……prophecy."</p><p>丹莫刺尔说：“启禀陛下，我相信自己这么说过。”他小心翼翼地望着这位皇帝，仿佛在斟酌自己该再说多少。“话说回来，果真如此的话，任何人的预言都没有两样。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Not……persons would be equally believed, Demerzel. A mathematician, however,……could back……prophecy with mathematical formulas……terminology, might be understood by no……and……believed by everyone."</p><p>“丹莫刺尔，并不是每个人都能令民众同样信服。然而，数学家却能用数学公式和术语来支持自己的预言。即使谁也不了解他说些什么，大家仍会深信不疑。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said,……usual, Sire,……make good sense. We live in troubled times……it would be worthwhile to calm them in a……that would require neither money……military effort……which, in recent history, have done little good……much harm."</p><p>丹莫刺尔说：“陛下，您的话总是很有道理。我们生在一个动荡的时代，值得借用一种既不费钱又不必采取军事行动的方式来稳定人心。反观近代史，军事行动总是弄巧成拙，反而造成很大的伤害。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Exactly, Demerzel," said……Emperor with excitement. "Reel in this Hari Seldon.……tell me……have your strings stretching to every part of this turbulent world, even where my forces dare……go, Pull on……of those strings, then,……bring in this mathematician.……me……him."</p><p>“丹莫刺尔，正是如此。”大帝兴奋地说，“把这个哈里·谢顿牵来。你告诉过我，你在这个纷乱的世界布满眼线，甚至渗透到连我的军队都退避的地方。那就抽回一根线吧，把这个数学家带来，让我见见他。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I will do so,Sire,"said Demerzel,……had already located Seldon……who made a mental note to commend……Minister of science……a……well donw.</p><p>“陛下，我立即去办。”丹莫刺尔说。其实他早已查出谢顿的下落，此时他暗自提醒自己，一定要嘉奖科学部长的优秀表现。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Hari Seldon……not make an impressive appearance at this time. Like……Emperor Cleon I, he……thirty-two years old,……he……only 1.73 meters tall.……face……smooth……cheerful,……hair dark brown, almost black,……his clothing……the unmistakable touch of provinciality about……</p><p>这个时期的哈里·谢顿貌不惊人。他与克里昂大帝一世一样，当年三十二岁，不过他的身高只有一米七三。他的脸庞光润，显得喜气洋洋，头发是接近黑色的深褐色，而他的衣着则带着一种一眼就看得出的土气。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>To anyone in later times……knew of Hari Seldon only as a legendary demigod, it would seem almost sacrilegious……him……to have white hair,……to have an……lined face, a quiet smile radiating wisdom,……to be seated in a wheelchair. Even then, in advanced……age,……eyes……been cheerful, however. There……that.</p><p>没有满头的白发、没有满是皱纹的脸庞、没有放射智慧光芒的微笑，而且并未坐在轮椅上的哈里·谢顿，对将他视为传奇性半人半神的后人而言，这种形象几乎可说是对他的亵渎。不过，即使到了耄耋高龄，谢顿的双眼依旧喜孜孜，那是他始终不变的特征。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And……eyes were particularly cheerful now,……his paper……been given at……Decennial Convention. It……even aroused some interest in a distant sort of……and……Osterfith……nodded……head at……and……said, "Ingenious, young man. Most ingenious." Which, coming from Osterfith,……satisfactory. Most satisfactory.</p><p>此时此刻，他那双眼睛显得特别喜气洋洋，因为他刚在“十载会议”上发表了一篇论文。这篇论文甚至多少引起了些许注意，老欧斯特费兹曾对他点了点头，说道：“有创意，年轻人，实在有创意。”这句话出自欧斯特费兹之口，令他觉得很有成就感，实在很有成就感。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>But……there……a new……and quite unexpected……development……Seldon wasnt sure whether it should increase……cheer……intensify……satisfaction or not. </p><p>可是现在却有一个新的……而且相当出乎意料的发展，谢顿不确定自己是否会因此更加喜孜孜，更有成就感。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He stared at……tall young……in uniform……the Spaceship-and-Sun neatly placed on……left side of……tunic.</p><p>他瞪着眼前这位人高马大、身穿制服的年轻人。在那人的短袖袍左胸处，有一个帅气的“星舰与太阳”标志。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Lieutenant Alban Wellis," said……officer of……Emperors Guard before putting away……identification. "Will……come with me now, sir?"</p><p>“艾尔本·卫利斯中尉。”将身份证件收起来之前，这位禁卫军军官曾自报姓名。“阁下，请您这就跟我走好吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Wellis……armed, of course. There were……other Guardsmen waiting outside……door. Seldon knew he……no choice,……all……others careful politeness,……there……no reason he could……seek information. He said,……see……Emperor?"</p><p>当然，卫利斯是全副武装前来的，此外还有两名禁卫军等在门外。尽管对方刻意表现得相当礼貌，谢顿却知道自己别无选择。但无论如何，他总有权把事情弄清楚，于是他说：“去觐见大帝？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"To be brought to……Palace, sir. Thats……extent of my instructions."</p><p>“阁下，是前往皇宫。我接到的命令仅止于此。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But why?"</p><p>“可是为什么呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I……not told why, sir.……I have my strict instructions that……must come with me……one……or another."</p><p>“阁下，我并不知情。我接到严格的命令，一定要您跟我前去……无论用什么方法。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But this seems as though I am being arrested. I have done nothing to warrant that."</p><p>“可是这样一来，好像我遭到逮捕了。我可没有犯什么法。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Say, rather, that it seems……are being given an escort of honor……if……delay me no further."</p><p>“应该这么说，好像是我们在为您护驾……请您别再耽误时间。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon delayed no further. He pressed……lips together, as though to block of further questions, nodded……head,……stepped forward. Even if he……going to meet……Emperor……to receive Imperial commendation, he found no……in……He……for……Empire……that……for……worlds of humanity in peace……union……he……not……the Emperor.</p><p>谢顿果然未曾再耽搁。他紧闭嘴唇，仿佛将其他疑问全部封在嘴里，点了点头之后，他便迈开脚步。即使他真要去觐见大帝，去接受皇室的嘉奖，他也觉得没什么意思。他的努力是为了整个帝国，换句话说，是为了所有人类世界的和平与团结，而不是为了这位皇帝。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The lieutenant walked ahead,……other……behind. Seldon smiled at those he passed……managed to look unconcerned. Outside……hotel they climbed into an official ground-car. (Seldon……his hand over……upholstery; he……never been in anything so ornate.)</p><p>中尉走在前面，另外那两名禁卫军殿后。谢顿对擦身而过的每个人报以微笑，设法表现得若无其事。出了旅馆之后，他们便登上一辆官方地面车。谢顿不禁伸手摸了摸椅套，他从未坐过这么豪华的车子。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>They were in……of……wealthiest sections of Trantor.……dome……high enough here to give a sensation of being in……open……one could swear……even……such as Hari Seldon,……had been born……brought up on an open world……that they were in sunlight.……could……no……and no shadows,……the……was light……fragrant.</p><p>他们目前所在的地点，是川陀最富有的地区之一。这里的穹顶相当高耸，足以带来置身露天空间的感觉。任何人都会发誓正沐浴在阳光下，就连生长在露天世界的哈里·谢顿也不例外。虽说见不到太阳或任何阴影，空气却显得明朗而清香。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And then it passed……the dome curved down……the walls narrowed in……soon they were moving along an enclosed tunnel, marked periodically with……Spaceship-and-Sun……so clearly reserved (Seldon thought)……official vehicles.</p><p>随着周遭的景物迅速后退，穹顶开始下弯，墙壁也变得越来越窄。他们很快就进入一座密闭的隧道，里面每隔固定距离就有一个“星舰与太阳”的标志，它显然（谢顿心想）专供官方交通工具使用。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>A door opened……the ground-car sped through. When……door closed behind them, they were in……open……the true,……real open. There were……square kilometers of……only stretch of open land on Trantor……on it stood……Imperial Palace. Seldon would have liked a chance to wander through that open land……not because of……Palace,……because it also contained……Galactic University and, most intriguing of all,……Galactic Library.</p><p>前面一道门及时打开，地面车快速穿过。当那道门重新关上之后，他们已经来到露天的空间……真正的露天空间。这里是川陀表面仅有的250平方公里露天地表，壮丽的皇宫正坐落其上。谢顿很希望有机会在这片土地上四处逛逛……并非由于皇宫，而是因为这里的帝国大学，以及最吸引他的帝国图书馆。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And yet, in passing from……enclosed world of Trantor into……open patch of wood……parkland, he……passed into a world in which clouds dimmed……sky……a chill wind rued……shirt. He pressed……contact that closed……ground-cars window.</p><p>然而，一旦离开密封在穹顶中的川陀，来到这个露天的林地与原野，他便置身于一个乌云遮日的世界，一阵寒风立刻袭上他的衣衫。他随手按下开关，把车窗关了起来。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>It……a dismal……outside.</p><p>外面是个阴冷的日子。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……not at……sure he would meet……Emperor. At best, he would meet some official in……fourth or fifth echelon……would claim to speak……the Emperor.</p><p>谢顿一点也不相信能见到皇帝陛下。在他想来，自己顶多只能见到某个四五等官位、自称代表皇帝发言的官员。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>How many people ever……see……Emperor? In person, rather than on holovision?……many people……the real, tangible Emperor, an Emperor……never left……Imperial grounds that……Seldon,……now rolling over. </p><p>究竟有多少人见过皇帝陛下？亲眼见到，而并非透过全息电视？有多少人见过真实的、有血有肉的皇帝陛下？这位大帝从不离开皇宫御苑，而他，谢顿，此时正踩在这片土地上。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The number……vanishingly small. Twenty-five million inhabited worlds, each with……cargo of a billion human beings or more……and among……those quadrillions of human beings,……many had, or would ever,……eyes on……living Emperor. A thousand?</p><p>答案几乎趋近于零。二千五百万个住人世界，每个世界的居民至少十亿之众……在这数万兆的人口中，有多少人曾经或将会目睹这位活生生的皇帝？一千人？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And……anyone care?……Emperor……no more than a symbol of Empire, like……Spaceship-and-Sun……far less pervasive,……less real. It……his soldiers……his officials, crawling everywhere, that……represented an Empire that……become a dead weight upon……people……not……Emperor.</p><p>又有谁会在乎呢？皇帝只不过是帝国的象征，就像“星舰与太阳”国徽一样，却远不及后者那么普遍与真实。如今代表帝国的，是遍布银河各个角落的战士与官吏；是他们变成人民身上的枷锁，而不是皇帝本人。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>So it……that when Seldon……ushered into a moderately sized, lavishly furnished room……found a young-looking……sitting on……edge of a table in a windowed alcove,……foot on……ground……one swinging over……edge, he found himself wondering that……official should be looking at……in so blandly good-natured a way. He……already experienced……fact, over……over, that government officials……and particularly those in……Imperial service……looked grave at……times, as though bearing……weight of……entire Galaxy on their shoulders.……it seemed……lower in importance they were,……graver……more threatening their expression.</p><p>因此，当他被引进一间不大不小、装潢豪奢的房间，看见一个年轻人坐在凹室的一张桌子旁，一只脚摆在地上，另一只放在桌缘摇晃，谢顿不禁纳闷怎么会有这样的官员，怎么会以这么温和的目光望着自己。他已经一而再、再而三体验到一件事实，那就是政府官员……尤其是皇帝身边当差的……总是显得十分严肃，仿佛将整个银河的重量担在自己肩上。而且似乎愈是不重要的官员，表情就愈严肃、愈凶恶。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>This, then, might be an official so high in……scale, with……sun of power so bright upon him, that he felt no need of countering it with clouds of frowning. </p><p>那么，此人就有可能是个官位很高的大官。他掌握的权力有如灿烂的阳光，因而不必利用一脸阴霾面对问题。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon wasn't sure……impressed he ought to……but he felt that it would be best to remain silent……let……other speak first. </p><p>谢顿不确定该表现得多么受宠若惊，但他感到自己最好保持缄默，让对方先开口。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The official said, "You……Hari Seldon, I believe.……mathematician."</p><p>那位官员说：“我相信你就是哈里·谢顿，那个数学家。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon responded with a minimal "Yes, sir,"……waited again.</p><p>谢顿以最简单的方式答道：“是的，阁下。”接着便继续等待。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The young……waved an arm.……should be Sire,……I hate ceremony.……all I……and I weary of……We……alone, so I will pamper myself……eschew ceremony.……down, professor."</p><p>年轻人挥了挥手臂。“应该说‘陛下’才对，不过我痛恨繁文缛节。我总是在繁文缛节里打转，这使我厌烦透顶。现在没有旁人，所以我要放纵一下，把繁文缛节抛到脑后。教授，坐吧。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Halfway through……speech, Seldon realized that he……speaking to……Emperor Cleon, First of that Name,……he felt……wind go……of him. There……a faint resemblance (now that he looked) to……official holograph that appeared constantly in……news,……in that holograph, Cleon……always dressed imposingly, seemed taller, nobler, frozen-faced. </p><p>对方讲到一半，谢顿便发觉面前这位正是克里昂大帝一世，这使他感到有点喘不过气来。大帝本人（现在看来）与新闻中经常出现的正式全息肖像有几分相似，不过全息像中的克里昂总是穿得雍容华贵，似乎比本人高大一些，尊贵一点，而且面孔冷漠，毫无表情。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And here he was,……original of……holograph,……somehow he appeared to be quite ordinary.</p><p>如今全息像的本尊出现在谢顿面前，却似乎显得相当平凡。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……not budge.</p><p>谢顿纹风不动。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The Emperor frowned slightly and, with……habit of command present even in……attempt to abolish……at least temporarily, said peremptorily, "I said,……down, man. That chair. Quickly."</p><p>大帝微微皱了皱眉头。他平常颐指气使惯了，此时虽想放弃这种特权，至少是暂时放弃，却仍然以专横的口吻说：“喂，我说‘坐吧’。那张椅子，快点。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……down, quite speechless. He could……even bring himself to say, "Yes, Sire."</p><p>谢顿默默坐下，他甚至连“遵命，陛下”也说不出口。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon smiled. "Thats better.……we……talk like……fellow human beings, which, after all, is what we……once ceremony is removed.……my man?"</p><p>克里昂微微一笑。“这样好多了。现在我们可以像两个同胞一样交谈了，毕竟，一旦除去一切繁文缛节，我们的关系就是这样。啊，你说是不是？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said cautiously,……Your Imperial Majesty is content to……so, then it is so."</p><p>谢顿小心翼翼地答道：“假如皇帝陛下喜欢这么说，那就一定没错。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Oh, come,……are……so cautious? I want to talk to……on equal terms. It is my pleasure to do……Humor me."</p><p>“喔，别这样，你为何如此小心谨慎？我想要以平等的身份和你交谈。这么做令我开心，你就顺着我吧。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yes, Sire."</p><p>“遵命，陛下。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"A simple Yes, man. Is there no……I……reach you?"</p><p>“只要简单一句‘遵命’就行了，我真没办法教会你吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon stared at Seldon……Seldon thought it……a lively……interested stare.</p><p>克里昂瞪着谢顿，谢顿觉得那双眼睛充满生气与兴味。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Finally……Emperor said, "You don't look like a mathematician."</p><p>最后，大帝总算再度开口：“你看来并不像数学家。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>At last, Seldon found himself able to smile. "I don't know what a mathematician is suppose to look like, Your Imp……"</p><p>谢顿终于能够露出笑容。“我不知道数学家应该像什么样子，皇帝陛……”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon raised a cautioning hand……Seldon choked……the honorific.</p><p>克里昂举起一只手来表示警告，谢顿赶紧咽下这个尊称。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p> Cleon said, "White-haired, I suppose. Bearded, perhaps. Old, certainly."</p><p>克里昂说：“我认为应该满头白发，或许还留着络腮胡。年纪当然有一大把。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yet even mathematicians must be young to begin with."</p><p>“但即使是数学家，也总有年轻的时候。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But they……then without reputation. By……time they obtrude themselves on……notice of……Galaxy, they……as I have described."</p><p>“可是那时他们都默默无闻。等到他们的名声传遍全银河，他们就是我所描述的那种模样。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I am without reputation, Im afraid."</p><p>“只怕我并没有什么名气。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yet……spoke at this convention they held here."</p><p>“但你曾在此地举行的会议上演讲。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"A great many of us did. Some were younger than myself.……of us were granted……attention whatever."</p><p>“许多人都上了台，有些比我还要年轻。却没有什么人受到注意。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Your talk apparently attracted……attention of some of my officials. I am given to understand that……believe it possible to predict……future."</p><p>“你的演讲显然吸引了我的一些官员注意。根据我的了解，你相信未来是有可能预测的。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon suddenly felt weary. It seemed as though this misinterpretation of……theory……constantly going to occur. Perhaps he should……have presented……paper.</p><p>谢顿突然感到一股倦意。似乎不断有人误解他的理论，或许他根本不该发表那篇论文。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He said, "Not quite, actually. What I have done is much more limited than that. In many systems,……situation is such that under some conditions chaotic events take place. That means that, given a particular starting point, it is impossible to predict outcomes. This is true even in some quite simple systems,……the more complex a system,……more likely it is to become chaotic. It……always been assumed that anything as complicated as human society would quickly become chaotic and, therefore, unpredictable. What I have done, however, is to show that, in studying human society, it is possible to choose a starting point……to make appropriate assumptions that will suppress……chaos. That will make it possible to predict……future,……in full detail, of course,……in broad sweeps;……with certainty,……with calculable probabilities."</p><p>他说：“并不尽然，我得到的结果其实狭隘得多。许多系统都会出现一种情形，那就是在某些条件下会产生混沌现象。这就意味着，针对某个特殊的起点，我们不可能预测后来的结果。甚至一些相当简单的系统也是这样，而系统愈复杂，就愈有可能变得混沌。过去我们一直假定，像人类社会这么复杂的东西，会在很短时间之内变得混沌，因此不可预测。然而，我所做到的则是证明，在研究人类社会时，有可能选择一个起点，并做出一组适当的假设，用以压抑混沌效应，使得预测未来变成可能。当然不是完整的细节，而是大致的趋势；并非绝对确定，但是可以计算其中的几率。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The Emperor,……had listened carefully, said, "But doesnt that mean that……have shown……to predict……future?"</p><p>一直仔细聆听的大帝这时问道：“可是，这不正意味着你示范了如何预测未来吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Again,……quite. I have showed that it is theoretically possible,……no more. To do more, we would actually have to choose a correct starting point, make correct assumptions,……then find ways of carrying through calculations in a finite time. Nothing in my mathematical argument tells us……to do……of this.……even if we could do it all, we would, at best, only assess probabilities. That is……the same as predicting……future; it is merely a guess at what is likely to happen. Every successful politician, businessman, or human being of……calling must make these estimates of……future……do it fairly well or he or……would……be successful."</p><p>“还是那句话，并不尽然。我证明了理论上的可能性，但仅止于此。想要进一步探究，我们必须真正选择一个正确的起点，并做出一组正确的假设，然后找出能在有限时间之内完成计算的方法。在我的数学论证中，完全没有提到应该如何进行这些。但即使我们通通做得到，顶多也只能估算出几率。这和预测未来并不相同，它只是猜测可能会发生些什么事。每一个成功的政治人物、商人，或是从事任何行业的人，都必须能对未来做出这样的估计，而且估计得相当准，否则他们不会成功。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"They do it without mathematics."</p><p>“他们并未用到数学。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"True. They do it by intuition."</p><p>“是的，他们凭借的是直觉。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"With……proper mathematics, anyone would be able to assess……probabilities. It wouldnt take……rare human being……is successful because of a remarkable intuitive sense."</p><p>“一旦掌握适当的数学工具，任何人都有办法估算几率。这样一来，少数具有优异直觉的成功人士便无法垄断了。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"True again,……I have merely shown that mathematical analysis is possible; I have……shown it to be practical."</p><p>“又说对了，但我只是证明这个数学分析是可能的，我并未证明它实际上可行。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"How……something be possible,……not practical?"</p><p>“一件事既然可能，又怎么会不可行呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It is theoretically possible……me to visit each world of……Galaxy……greet each person on each world. However, it would take……longer to do this than I have years to live and, even if I……immortal,……rate at which……human beings……being born is greater than……rate at which I could interview……old and, even more to……point,……human beings would……in great numbers before I could ever……to them."</p><p>“理论上，我可以造访银河系每一个世界，和每个世界上的每个人打招呼。然而，完成这项工作需要很长的时间，远超过我一生的寿命。即使我能长生不死，新一代出生的速率也会大于我拜访老一辈的速率。更重要的是，许多老一辈在等不及我拜访他们之前便会死去。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"And is this sort of thing true of your mathematics of……future?" </p><p>“在你的有关未来的数学理论中，情况是不是真的这样？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon hesitated, then went……"It might be that……mathematics would take……long to work out, even if……had a computer……size of……Universe working at hyperspatial velocities. By……time……answer……been received, enough years would have elapsed to alter……situation so grossly as to make……answer meaningless."</p><p>谢顿迟疑了一下，然后继续说：“这个数学计算或许要花太长的时间才能完成，即使我们有一台和宇宙同样大的电脑，以超空间速度运作也于事无补。在获得任何答案之际，岁月早已流逝多年，情势则已发生巨大变化，足以使得答案变得毫无意义。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Why cannot……process be simplified?" Cleon asked sharply.</p><p>“过程为什么不能简化呢？”克里昂严厉地问道。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Your Imperial Majesty,"……Seldon felt……Emperor growing more formal as……answers grew less to……liking……responded with greater formality of……own, "consider……manner in which scientists have dealt with subatomic particles. There……enormous numbers of these, each moving or vibrating in random……unpredictable manner,……this chaos turns……to have an underlying order, so that we……work……a quantum mechanics that answers……the questions we know……to ask. In studying society, we place human beings in……place of subatomic particles,……now there is……added factor of……human mind. Particles move mindlessly; human beings do not. To take into account……various attitudes……impulses of mind adds so much complexity that there lacks time to take care of……of it."</p><p>“皇帝陛下，”谢顿感到随着答案越来越不合胃口，大帝的口气变得越来越正式，便决定用最正式的方式回应。“想想科学家处理次原子粒子的方式。那些粒子数量十分庞大，每一个都以随机而不可预测的方式运动或振动。但是这个混沌的底层藏有一种秩序，所以我们才能创立量子力学，用以回答所有我们知道该如何问的问题。而在研究社会现象时，我们将人类摆在次原子粒子的地位，不同的是此时多了一项变因，那就是人类的心灵。粒子以无意识的方式运动，人类则不然。若想将心灵中各种态度与冲动考虑在内，会使得复杂度增加太多，令我们根本没有时间面面顾到。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Could……mind, as well as mindless motion, have an underlying order?"</p><p>“心灵会不会和粒子的无意识运动一样，也存在一个底层的秩序呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Perhaps. My mathematical analysis implies that order must underlie everything, however disorderly it……appear to……but it does……give……hint as to……this underlying order……be found. Consider……Twenty-five million worlds, each with……overall characteristics……culture, each being significantly different from……the rest, each containing a billion or more human beings……each have an individual mind,……all……worlds interacting in innumerable ways……combinations! However theoretically possible a psychohistorical analysis……be, it is……likely that it……be done in……practical sense."</p><p>“或许吧。根据我的数学分析，不论表面上看来多么杂乱无章，任何事物背后都必定藏有秩序。至于如何找出这些底层的秩序，这套数学却完全没有提示。想想看……两千五百万个世界，每一个都有整体的特征与文化，每一个都和其他世界大不相同，每一个都至少包含十亿人口，人人又各自拥有一个独立的心灵，而所有这些世界，则以数不清的方式和组合在进行互动。不论心理史学分析在理论上多么可能，却难以有什么实际上的应用。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"What do……mean psychohistorical?"</p><p>“你所谓的‘心理史学’是什么意思？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I refer to……theoretical assessment of probabilities concerning……future as psychohistory. "</p><p>“我将‘对未来的理论性几率估算’称为心理史学。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The Emperor rose to……feet suddenly, strode to……other……of……room, turned, strode back,……stopped before……still-sitting Seldon. </p><p>大帝突然起身，大步走向房间另一侧，然后一个转身，又大步走回来，驻足于仍坐着的谢顿面前。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Stand……he commanded.</p><p>“站起来！”他命令道。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon rose……looked up at……somewhat taller Emperor. He strove to keep……gaze steady.</p><p>谢顿赶紧起立，抬头望着比自己高几分的大帝，勉力维持自己的目光坚定不移。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon finally said, "This psychohistory of yours……if it could be made practical, it would be of great use, would it not?"</p><p>克里昂终于开口：“你的这个心理史学……假如能变得实际可行，会有很大的用处，对不对？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Of enormous use, obviously. To know what……future holds, in even……most general……probabilistic way, would serve as a……and marvelous guide……our actions,……that humanity……never before had. But, of course……" He paused.</p><p>“显然会有极大的用处。若能知道未来有些什么，即使是以最概略性、最几率性的方式，也能为我们的行动提供一个崭新而绝佳的指导，这乃是人类从未掌握的。可是，当然……”他突然住口。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well?" said Cleon impatiently.</p><p>“怎么样？”克里昂不耐烦地说。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well, it would seem that, except……a……decision-makers,……results of psychohistorical analysis would have to remain unknown to……public."</p><p>“嗯，情况似乎是这样的，除了少数决策者之外，心理史学分析的结果必须对大众保密。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Unknown!" exclaimed Cleon with surprise.</p><p>“保密！”克里昂高声惊叫。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Its clear.……me……to explain. If a psychohistorical analysis is made……the results……then given to……public,……various emotions……reactions of humanity would at once be distorted.……psychohistorical analysis, based on emotions……reactions that take place without knowledge of……future, become meaningless. Do……understand?"</p><p>“这很明显，让我试着解释一下。假如我们完成一个心理史学分析，并将结果公诸于世，人类的种种情绪和种种反应必将立刻受到扭曲。这样一来，心理史学分析就会变得毫无意义，因为它所根据的，是众人对未来不知情的情况下所产生的情绪和反应。您了解我的意思吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The Emperors eyes brightened……he laughed aloud. "Wonderful!" </p><p>大帝突然眼睛一亮，哈哈大笑几声。“太好了！”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He clapped……hand on Seldons shoulder……Seldon staggered slightly under……blow.</p><p>他伸手拍了拍谢顿的肩膀，谢顿不禁轻轻晃了一下。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Dont……see, man?" said Cleon. "Dont……see? Theres your use.……don't need to predict……future. Just choose a future……a good future, a useful future……and make……kind of prediction that will alter human emotions……reactions in such a……that……future……predicted will be brought about. Better to make a good future than predict a……one."</p><p>“你这个人，你看不出来吗？”克里昂说，“难道你看不出来吗？这就是你的用处。你根本不需要预测未来，而只要选择一个未来……一个好的未来、一个有用的未来……然后做出一种预测，让所有人类的情绪和反应都发生变化，以便实现你预测的那个未来。与其预测一个坏的未来，不如制造一个好的未来。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon frowned. "I……what……mean, Sire,……that is equally impossible."</p><p>谢顿皱起眉头。“启禀陛下，我懂得您的意思，但这同样是不可能的事。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Impossible?"</p><p>“不可能？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well, at……rate, impractical. don't……see? If……cant start with human emotions……reactions……predict……future they will bring about,……cant do……reverse either.……cant start with a future……predict……human emotions……reactions that will bring it about."</p><p>“嗯，至少是不切实际。您看不出来吗？倘若我们不能从人类的情绪和反应出发，不能预测这些因素所将导致的未来，那就同样无法反其道而行。我们不能从一个选定的未来出发，反推它的源头是哪些人类情绪和反应。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon looked frustrated.……lips tightened. "And your paper, then?……Is that what……call……a paper?……Of what……is it?"</p><p>克里昂显得相当沮丧，紧紧抿着嘴唇。“那么，你的论文呢？……你是不是管它叫论文？……它又有什么用呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It……merely a mathematical demonstration. It made a point of interest to mathematicians,……there……no thought in my mind of……being useful in……way."</p><p>“那只是一种数学论证。它提出一个令数学家感兴趣的结论，但我从未想到会有任何实际用途。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I find that disgusting," said Cleon angrily.</p><p>“我发觉这实在可恶。”克里昂气呼呼地说。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon shrugged slightly. More than ever, he knew he should never have given……paper. What would become of……if……Emperor took it into……head that he……been made to play……fool?</p><p>谢顿微微耸了耸肩。他现在更加确定一件事，自己根本不该发表那篇论文。假如大帝自认为成了别人愚弄的对象，自己会有什么样的下场呢？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And indeed, Cleon……not look as though he……very……from believing that. </p><p>事实上，克里昂看来像是快要相信这一点了。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Nevertheless, he said, "what if……were to make predictions of……future, mathematically justified or not; predictions that government officials, human beings whose expertise it is to know what……public is likely to……will judge to be……kind that will bring about useful reactions?"</p><p>“话说回来，”他说，“假如你对未来做出一些预测，不论是否在数学上站得住脚，但根据那些了解大众趋向的政府官员判断，它们就是会带来有用的反应，你认为如何？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Why would……need me to do that?……government officials could make those predictions themselves……spare……middleman."</p><p>“您为何需要由我做这件事？政府官员自己就能做这些预测，不必假手中间人。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"The government officials could……do so as effectively. Government officials do make statements of……sort……and then. They……not necessarily believed."</p><p>“政府官员做来不会那么有效。他们的确偶尔会发表这类的声明，可是民众不一定相信他们。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Why would I be?"</p><p>“为何又会相信我呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You……a mathematician.……would have calculated……future, not……not intuited it……if that is a word."</p><p>“你是个数学家，你会‘计算’未来，而不是……不是去直觉它……如果可以这样说的话。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But I would……have done so."</p><p>“可是我并没有这个能力。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Who would know that?" Cleon watched……out of narrowed eyes. There……a pause.</p><p>“谁会知道呢？”克里昂眯起眼睛望着他。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon felt trapped. If given a direct order by……Emperor, would it be safe to refuse? If he refused, he might be imprisoned or executed.……without trial, of course,……it is only with great difficulty that a trial……be made to go against……wishes of a heavy-handed officialdom, particularly……under……command of……Emperor of……vast Galactic Empire. </p><p>接下来是短暂的沉默。谢顿感到自己中计了。假如大帝直接对他下令，他敢拒绝吗？若是拒绝，他也许就会遭到监禁或处决。当然不会没有审判，可是面对一个专制的官僚体制，尤其是银河帝国的皇帝指挥之下的极权官僚体制，想要获得公平审判是难上加难。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He said finally,……wouldnt work."</p><p>最后，他终于答道：“这样行不通。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Why not?"</p><p>“为什么？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"If I were asked to predict vague generalities that could……possibly come to pass until long after this generation and, perhaps,……next were dead, we might……away with……but, on……other hand,……public would……little attention. They would……care about a glowing eventuality a century or……in……future.</p><p>“假如要我做出一些含糊的一般性预测，必须等到我们这一代，甚至下一代死后多年才有可能实现，那么也许可以蒙混过去。可是，这样一来，民众却不会如何留意。对于一两个世纪之后才会发生的重大事件，他们是不可能关心的。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"To attain results," Seldon went……"I would have to predict matters of sharper consequence, more immediate eventualities. Only to these would……public respond. Sooner or later, though……and probably sooner……one of……eventualities would……come to pass……my usefulness would be ended at once. With that, your popularity might be gone, too, and, worst of all, there would be no further support……the development of psychohistory so that there would be no chance……any good to come of it if future improvements in mathematical insights help to make it move closer to……realm of practicality."</p><p>“为了获得成果，”谢顿继续说，“我必须预测一些结果较为明确的事件，或是一些近在眼前的变故。只有这种预测才能获得大众的回应。不过迟早……也许不会迟只会早……其中一项预测并不会实现，而我的利用价值将立刻结束。这样一来，您的声望也可能随之消失。更糟的是，以后再也不会有人支持心理史学的发展，即使未来的数学能将它改良到接近实用的程度，它也不会再有大显身手的机会了。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon threw himself into a chair……frowned at Seldon.……that……you mathematicians……do? Insist on impossibilities?"</p><p>克里昂猛然坐下，对着谢顿皱起眉头。“你们数学家能做的就是这件事吗？坚持各种的不可能？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said with desperate softness,……is you, Sire,……insist on impossibilities."</p><p>谢顿拼了命以和缓的语调说：“是您，陛下，在坚持一些不可能的事。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Let me test you, man. Suppose I asked……to……your mathematics to tell me whether I would some……be assassinated? What would……say?"</p><p>“你这个人，让我来测验你一下。假如我要你利用你的数学告诉我，是否有朝一日我会遇刺身亡，你会怎么说？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"My mathematical system would……give an answer to so specific a question, even if psychohistory worked at……best.……the quantum mechanics in……world cannot make it possible to predict……behavior of……lone electron, only……average behavior of many."</p><p>“即使将心理史学发挥到极致，这个数学体系仍然无法回答如此特定的问题。全世界的量子力学专家同心协力，也不可能预测单独一个电子的踪迹，而只能预测众多电子的平均行为。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You know your mathematics better than I……Make an educated guess based on……Will I someday be assassinated?"</p><p>“你比我更了解你自己的数学理论，就根据它做个合理的猜测吧。我是否有朝一日会遇刺？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said softly, "You……a trap……me, Sire. Either tell me what answer……wish……I will give it to……or else give me free right to make what answer I wish without punishment."</p><p>谢顿柔声答道：“陛下，您这是对我设下圈套。干脆告诉我您想要听什么答案，我好直接说出来，否则就请授权给我，让我自由回答而不至招罪。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Speak as……will."</p><p>“你尽管说吧。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Your word of honor?"</p><p>“您以荣誉担保？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Do……want it an writing?" Cleon……sarcastic.</p><p>“你要我立下字据吗？”克里昂语带讥讽。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Your spoken word of honor will be sufficient," said Seldon,……heart sinking,……he……not certain it would be.</p><p>“有您口头的荣誉担保就够了。”谢顿的心往下沉，因为他不确定会有什么结果。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You have my word of honor."</p><p>“我以荣誉担保。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Then I……tell……that in……past four centuries nearly half……Emperors have been assassinated, from which I conclude that……chances of your assassination……roughly……in two."</p><p>“那么我可以告诉您，在过去四个世纪中，几乎有一半的皇帝遇刺身亡，根据这一点，我推断您遇刺的机会约略是二分之一。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Any fool……give that answer," said Cleon with contempt.……takes no mathematician."</p><p>“任何傻瓜都能说出这个答案。”克里昂以轻蔑的口吻说，“根本不需要数学家。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yet I have told……several times that my mathematics is useless……practical problems."</p><p>“可是我跟您说过好几次了，我的数学理论对实际问题毫无用处。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Cant……even suppose that I learn……lessons that have been given me by my unfortunate predecessors?"</p><p>“难道你就不能假设，我从那些不幸的先帝身上学到教训了？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon took a deep breath……plunged……"No, Sire.……history shows that we do……learn from……lessons of……past.……instance,……have allowed me here in a private audience. What if it were in my mind to assassinate you? Which it isnt, Sire," he added hastily.</p><p>谢顿深深吸了一口气，一鼓作气道：“不能的，陛下。历史在在显示，我们无法从历史中学到任何教训。举例而言，您准许我在这里单独觐见，万一我有心行刺呢？这当然不是事实，陛下。”他赶紧补充一句。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon smiled without humor.……man,……don't take into account……thoroughness……or advances in technology. We have studied your history, your complete record. When……arrived,……were scanned. Your expression……voiceprints were analyzed. We knew your emotional state in detail; we practically knew your thoughts.……there been……slightest doubt of your harmlessness,……would……have been allowed near……In fact,……would……now be alive."</p><p>克里昂冷冷一笑。“你这个人，你没有考虑到我们的科技多么完善……或说多么先进。我们研究过你的背景，以及你的完整履历。在你抵达后，你就接受了扫描，你的面容和声纹都经过分析。我们知道你详尽的情绪状态，几乎可以说知道你的思想。对你的忠贞若有丝毫怀疑，就绝不会允许你接近我。事实上，是你根本活不到现在。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>A wave of nausea swept through Seldon,……he continued. "Outsiders have always found it difficult to……at Emperors, even with technology less advanced. However, almost every assassination……been a palace coup. It is those nearest……Emperor……are……greatest danger to him. Against that danger,……careful screening of outsiders is irrelevant.……as……your……officials, your……Guardsmen, your……intimates,……cannot treat them as……treat me."</p><p>谢顿感到一阵晕眩，不过他继续说：“即使没有那么先进的科技，外人也总是难以接近任何一位皇帝。然而，几乎每次行刺都源自宫廷政变。对皇帝构成最大威胁的，就是最接近皇帝的人。想要趋吉避凶，细查外人其实无济于事。至于您自己的官员、您自己的禁卫军、您自己的亲信，您总不能以对待我的方式对待他们。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon said, "I know that, too,……at least as well as……do.……answer is that I treat those about me fairly……I give them no cause……resentment."</p><p>克里昂说：“这点我也知道，至少和你一样清楚。我的回答是，我对身边每个人都很好，让他们没有怨恨我的理由。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"A foolish……" began Seldon,……then stopped in confusion.</p><p>“愚蠢……”说到这里谢顿突然住口，显得十分狼狈。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Go on," said Cleon angrily. "I have given……permission to speak freely.……am I foolish?"</p><p>“继续，”克里昂怒冲冲地说，“我已经准许你自由发表意见。我如何愚蠢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"The word slipped out, Sire. I meant irrelevant. Your treatment of your intimates is irrelevant.……must be suspicious; it would be inhuman……to……A careless word, such as……one I used, a careless gesture, a doubtful expression……you must withdraw a……with narrowed eyes.……any touch of suspicion sets in motion a vicious cycle.……intimate will sense……resent……suspicion……will develop a changed behavior,……as he might to avoid……You sense that……grow more suspicious and, in……end, either he is executed or……are assassinated. It is a process that……proved unavoidable……the Emperors of……past four centuries……it is……one sign of……increasing difficulty of conducting……affairs of……Empire."</p><p>“启禀陛下，我说溜了嘴。我原本想说的是‘无关’，这和您如何对待亲信根本无关。您一定会疑神疑鬼，否则就不符合人性。一个不经意的字眼……例如我刚才的表现，或是一个不经意的动作、一个可疑的表情，都必定会令您提高警觉，并收回一点信任。而任何猜疑都将造成恶性循环……那位亲信感觉得到，他会恼恨您的疑心，并会改变他的言行举止，尽可能避免让您再度起疑；您则会察觉这个变化，因而疑心越来越重，到头来不是他被处决，就是您遇刺身亡。过去四个世纪的好多位皇帝，都无法避免这样的过程。帝国事务变得越来越难处理，这只是征兆之一。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Then nothing I……do will avoid assassination."</p><p>“那么，我无论如何无法避免遇刺喽。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"No, Sire," said Seldon, "but, on……other hand,……may prove fortunate."</p><p>“是的，陛下。”谢顿说，“不过，反之，您也可能属于幸运的那一半。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleons fingers were drumming on……arm of……chair. He said harshly, "You……useless, man,……so is your psychohistory. Leave me."……with those words,……Emperor looked away, suddenly seeming much older than……thirty-two years.</p><p>克里昂用手指轮流敲打座椅扶手，然后厉声道：“你这个人，你根本没用，你的心理史学也一样。给我走吧。”说完这几句话，大帝转过头去，突然好像比三十二岁的实际年龄老了许多。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I have said my mathematics would be useless to you, Sire. My profound apologies." Seldon tried to……but at some signal he……not see,……guards entered……took……away.</p><p>“启禀陛下，我早就说过，我的数学理论对您没用。我致上最深的歉意。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleons voice came after……from……royal chamber. "Return that……to……place from which he……brought earlier."</p><p>谢顿本来准备鞠躬，但两名卫士不知如何接到了讯号，及时进来将他带走。御书房中还传出克里昂的一句：“这个人从哪里来，就把他送回哪里去。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Eto Demerzel emerged……glanced at……Emperor with a hint of proper deference. He said, "Sire,……have almost lost your temper."</p><p>伊图·丹莫刺尔适时出现，以适度尊崇的眼神瞥了大帝一眼。“陛下，您差点就发脾气了。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon looked up and, with an obvious effort, managed to smile. "Well, so I did.……man……very disappointing."</p><p>克里昂抬起头来，挤出一个显然很勉强的微笑。“嗯，没错。那人实在令我非常失望。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"And……he promised no more than he offered."</p><p>“但他并未做出能力范围外的承诺。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He offered nothing."</p><p>“他一点能力也没有。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"And promised nothing, Sire."</p><p>“也就没有做任何承诺，陛下。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It……disappointing."</p><p>“真令人失望。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said, "More than disappointing, perhaps.……man is a loose cannon, Sire."</p><p>丹莫刺尔说：“或许不只令人失望而已。这人是一颗流弹，陛下。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"A loose what, Demerzel?……are always so full of strange expressions. What is a cannon?"</p><p>“一颗流什么，丹莫刺尔？你总是喜欢用许多古怪的词句。流弹又是什么？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said gravely,……is simply an expression I heard in my youth, Sire.……Empire is full of strange expressions……some……unknown on Trantor, as those of Trantor……sometimes unknown elsewhere."</p><p>丹莫刺尔以严肃的口吻说：“启禀陛下，这不过是我年轻时听到的一种说法。帝国境内充满古怪的词句，有些是川陀从未听说过的，正如同川陀的某些惯用语，其他地方的人也听不懂一样。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Do……come to teach me……Empire is large? What do……mean by saying that……man is a loose cannon?"</p><p>“你是来提醒我帝国疆域的辽阔？你说那人是一颗流弹，这到底是什么意思？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Only that he……do much harm without necessarily intending……He does……know……own strength. Or importance."</p><p>“只是指他可能犯下无心之失，造成重大伤害。他不知道自己的力量，或者说重要性。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You deduce that, do you, Demerzel?"</p><p>“你推论出来的吗，丹莫刺尔？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yes, Sire. He is a provincial. He does……know Trantor or……ways. He……never been on……planet before……he cannot behave like a……of breeding, like a courtier.……he stood up to……"</p><p>“是的，陛下。他是个乡下人，并不了解川陀这个地方以及此地的规矩。他以前从未到过我们的行星，以致无法表现得像个有教养的人，比如说像个廷臣。但是他竟然敢跟您顶嘴。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"And……not? I gave……permission to speak. I left……ceremony. I treated……as an equal."</p><p>“有何不可？我准许他有话直说。我取消了繁文缛节，以平等的方式对待他。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Not entirely, Sire.……don't have it within……to treat others as equals.……have……habit of command.……even if……tried to……a person at……ease, there would be……who could manage……Most would be speechless……worse, subservient……sycophantic. This……stood up to you."</p><p>“启禀陛下，并不尽然。您天生就无法平等对待他人，您习惯于发号施令。即使您试图让对方轻松自在，也很少有人能做到这一点。大多数人会变得哑口无言，更糟的表现则是奉承和阿谀。可是，那人却跟您顶嘴。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well,……may admire that, Demerzel,……I didnt like him." Cleon looked thoughtfully discontented. "Did……notice that he made no effort to explain……mathematics to……It……as though he knew I would……understand a word of it."</p><p>“嗯，丹莫刺尔，你可以认为这很了不起，但是我不喜欢他。”克里昂看来十分不满，“你注意到了吗？他并没有尝试对我解释他的数学理论，好像他知道我一个字也听不懂。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Nor would……have, Sire.……are……a mathematician,……a scientist of……kind,……an artist. There……many fields of knowledge in which others know more than you. It is their task to……their knowledge to serve you.……are……Emperor, which is worth……their specializations……together."</p><p>“启禀陛下，您的确听不懂。您不是数学家，也不是任何领域的科学家，同时也不是艺术家。在许许多多的知识领域，都有人比您懂得还多，他们的职责就是利用这些知识为您服务。您是皇帝，这点就不亚于他们所有专长的总和。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Is……I would……mind being made to feel ignorant by an……man……had accumulated knowledge over many years.……this man, Seldon, is just my age.……does he know so much?"</p><p>“是吗？如果是个花了许多岁月累积知识的老头，令我感到自己某方面一窍不通，那我倒也不在意。可是这个人，谢顿，只不过和我同年。他怎么会知道那么多？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He……not……to learn……habit of command,……art of reaching a decision that will affect……lives of others."</p><p>“他不必学习领袖气质，也不必学习如何做出左右他人生死的决策。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Sometimes, Demerzel, I wonder if……are laughing at me."</p><p>“有些时候，丹莫刺尔，我会怀疑你是不是在讥笑我。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Sire?" said Demerzel reproachfully.</p><p>“陛下？”丹莫刺尔以责难的口吻说。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But never mind. Back to that loose cannon of yours.……should……consider……dangerous? He seems a naive provincial to me."</p><p>“不过算了吧，回到你刚才说的那个流弹。你为什么要认为他是危险人物？在我看来，他似乎是个纯真的乡下人。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He……But he……this mathematical development of his."</p><p>“没错，可是他拥有那套数学理论。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He says it is useless."</p><p>“他说那根本没用。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You thought it might be useful. I thought……after……had explained it to……Others might.……mathematician……come to think so himself,……that……mind……been focused on……And……knows, he……yet work……some……of making……of……If he does, then to foretell……future, however mistily, is to be in a position of great power. Even if he does……wish power……himself, a kind of self-denial that always seems to me to be unlikely, he might be used by others."</p><p>“您本来认为它也许有用。而在您向我解释之后，我也这么以为，所以其他人也有可能抱持同样的看法。既然这位数学家已经将心思集中在这个问题上，他自己的想法或许也会改变。谁知道呢，他也许会研究出利用这套数学的方法。假如他成功了，有办法预测未来了，不论多么朦胧模糊，他也等于掌握了极大的权力。即使他自己不希望拥有权力……我总认为如此自制的人少之又少……他也可能被别人利用。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I tried to……him. He would not."</p><p>“我试图利用他，可是他不肯。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He……not given it thought. Perhaps……he will.……if he……not interested in being used by you, might he……be persuaded by……let us say……the Mayor of Wye?"</p><p>“刚刚他没有好好考虑，也许现在他就会愿意。他若不喜欢被您利用，难道就不可能被……比方说……卫荷区长说服吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Why should he be willing to help……and……us?"</p><p>“他为什么会愿意帮助卫荷区长，而不愿帮我们？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"As he explained, it is hard to predict……emotions……behavior of individuals."</p><p>“正如他刚才的解释，个体的情绪和行为是很难预测的。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon scowled……sat in thought.……you really think he might develop this psychohistory of……to……point where it is truly useful? He is so certain he cannot."</p><p>克里昂绷着脸，坐在那里沉思良久。“你真的认为，他有可能将他的心理史学发展到真正有用的地步？他十分肯定自己做不到这一点。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He may, with time, decide he……wrong in denying……possibility."</p><p>“或许若干时日之后，他会发现否认这个可能性是个错误。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon said, "Then I suppose I ought to have kept him."</p><p>克里昂道：“这么说，我想我该把他留下。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said, "No, Sire. Your instinct……correct when……let……go. Imprisonment, however disguised, would cause resentment……despair, which would……help……either to develop……ideas further or make……eager to help……Better to……him go as……have done,……to keep……forever on an invisible leash. In this way, we……see that he is……used by an enemy of yourself, Sire,……we……see that when……time comes……he……fully developed……science, we……pull on……leash……bring……in. Then we could be……more persuasive."</p><p>丹莫刺尔说：“不然，陛下，当您让他离去时，您的直觉完全正确。倘若将他囚禁，无论做得多么不着痕迹，都将引起他的愤恨和绝望。这样不但无助于他进一步发展他的理论，也无法使他心甘情愿为我们服务。最好还是放他走，如您所做的那样，但是永远用一条隐形的绳索拴住他。这样一来，我们就能确定他不至于被陛下的敌人利用，也可以确定等到时机成熟，他将这个科学理论发展完备时，我们便能收回那条绳索，再把他拉进来。那个时候，我们可以……态度强硬一点。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But what if he it picked up by an enemy of mine……better, of……Empire,……I am……Empire after all, or……of……own accord, he wishes to serve an enemy……I don't consider that……of……question,……see."</p><p>“可是，万一他被我的敌人抓走，或者应该说帝国的敌人，毕竟我就等于这个帝国，还有，如果他自愿为敌人效命呢？我不认为这点绝无可能，你了解吧。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Nor should you. I will……to it that this doesnt happen,……if, against……striving, it does happen, it would be better if no……has……than if……wrong person does."</p><p>“您的顾虑没错。我会确保不至于发生这种事，但是，倘若尽了最大努力，仍然出现这种情形，与其让不适当的人拥有他，倒不如让谁都得不到。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Cleon looked uneasy. "Ill leave that……in your hands, Demerzel,……I hope were……too hasty. He could……after all, nothing……the purveyor of a theoretical science that does……and cannot work."</p><p>克里昂显得相当不安。“丹莫刺尔，我将这件事完全交到你手上，但我希望我们不要操之过急。无论如何，他有可能只是个理论科学的买办，并没有什么真正的用处。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Quite possibly, Sire,……it would be safer to assume……man is……or might be……important. We lose only a little time……nothing more if we find that we have concerned ourselves with a nonentity. We……lose a Galaxy if we find we have ignored someone of great importance."</p><p>“启禀陛下，很有可能，不过为了安全起见，最好还是假设此人很重要……或者说也许很重要。假使到头来，我们发现只是在为一个无足轻重的角色伤脑筋，那不过浪费了一点时间而已，不会有其他损失。但如果我们最后发现，忽略了一个再重要不过的人物，那我们将会丢掉整个银河。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Very well, then," said Cleon, "but I trust I wont have to know……details……if they prove unpleasant."</p><p>“这样很好，”克里昂说，“但我确信我不必知道细节……倘若细节果真令人不快。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Demerzel said, "Let us hope that will……be……case."</p><p>丹莫刺尔说：“让我们期望不会有那种结果。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……an evening, a night,……part of a morning to……over……meeting with……Emperor. At least,……changing quality of light within……walkways, moving corridors, squares,……parks of……Imperial Sector of Trantor made it seem that an evening, a night,……part of a morning……passed. </p><p>经过了一个黄昏、整个夜晚，以及半个上午的时光，谢顿慢慢从觐见大帝的情绪中恢复过来。至少，川陀皇区里的人行道、活动回廊、广场与公园的光线明暗变化，使人觉得已历经了一个黄昏、整个夜晚，以及第二天的半个上午。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He……now in a small park on a small plastic seat that molded itself neatly to……body……he……comfortable. Judging from……light, it seemed to be midmorning……the……was just cool enough to seem fresh without possessing even……smallest bite.</p><p>此刻，他坐在一座小公园的一张小型塑胶椅上，那椅子弯成与他的身躯刚好吻合的形状，令他感到非常舒服。根据光线判断，上午似乎刚过一半，空气凉爽适中，刚好使人感到清新，却一点也没有寒意。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Was it like this……the time? He thought of……gray……outside when he went to……the Emperor.……he thought of……the gray days……cold days……hot days……rainy days……snowy days on Helicon,……home,……he wondered if……could miss them.……it possible to……in a park on Trantor, having ideal weather……after day, so that it felt as though……were surrounded by nothing at all……and coming to miss a howling wind or a biting cold or a breathless humidity?</p><p>气候是否总是这样？他想到了觐见大帝时遇到的那种灰暗天气。然后，他又想起故乡赫利肯星的阴天、冷天、热天、雨天以及下雪天，不禁怀疑有谁会怀念那种日子。坐在川陀的一座公园里，日复一日都是理想的天气，几乎令人感到周遭一片虚空，还有没有可能会怀念怒吼的狂风、刺骨的寒冷，或是令人窒息的湿气？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Perhaps.……not on……first……or……second or……seventh. He would have only this……day……he would leave tomorrow. He meant to enjoy it while he could. He might, after all, never return to Trantor. </p><p>或许会吧，但不是在第一天、第二天，甚至第七天上头。而他只剩下今天最后一天，明天即将离开此地。他打定主意趁机享受一番，毕竟，自己可能再也不会重返川陀。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Still, he continued to feel uneasy at having spoken as independently as he……to a……who could, at will, order ones imprisonment or execution……or, at……very least,……economic……social death of loss of position……status. </p><p>然而，他仍旧感到惴惴不安，始终无法忘怀曾在没有其他人在场的情况下，和一个能随意下令监禁或处决任何人的人（至少他能剥夺他人的社会地位，造成一种经济性与社会性的死亡）做过一次晤谈。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Before going to bed, Seldon……looked up Cleon I in……encyclopedic portion of……hotel room computer.……Emperor……been highly praised……no doubt,?……Emperors in their……lifetime, regardless of their deeds. Seldon……dismissed that,……he……interested in……fact that Cleon……been born in……Palace……had never left……grounds. He……never been in Trantor itself, in……part of……multi-domed world. It……a matter of security, perhaps,……what it meant……that……Emperor……in prison, whether he admitted……matter to himself or not. It might be……most luxurious prison in……Galaxy,……it……a prison just……same.</p><p>就寝之前，谢顿利用旅馆房间的电脑，从电子百科全书查到了克里昂一世的资料。内容照例是为这位皇帝歌功颂德，就像所有的皇帝生前所受到的歌颂一样，与他们的政绩毫无关系。谢顿略过那些内容，他感兴趣的是发现克里昂生于皇宫，一生从未离开御苑。他从来没有到过真正的川陀……这个覆盖着多面穹顶的世界。也许这是基于安全考量，但它代表的则是这位皇帝一直遭到囚禁，不论他自己是否承认这一点。那可能是全银河最豪华的牢狱，但无论如何还是牢狱。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And though……Emperor……seemed mild-mannered……had shown no sign of being a bloody-minded autocrat as so many of……predecessors……been, it……not good to have attracted……attention. Seldon welcomed……thought of leaving tomorrow……Helicon, even though it would be winter (and a rather nasty one, so far) back home.</p><p>尽管这位皇帝似乎相当温和，一点也不像历代多位嗜血的独裁暴君，但引起他的注意总不是好事。谢顿很高兴明天就要回赫利肯，虽说家乡如今正值冬季（而且是个酷寒的冬季）。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He looked up at……bright diffuse light. Although it could never rain in here,……atmosphere……far from dry. A fountain played……far from him;……plants were green……had probably never felt drought. Occasionally,……shrubbery rustled as though a small animal or……was hidden there. He heard……hum of bees.</p><p>他抬头望了望漫射的明亮光线。虽然此地永远不会下雨，大气却绝对不算干燥。离他不远处有一座喷泉；植物是绿油油的一片，或许从未尝过干旱的滋味。灌木丛偶尔会沙沙作响，好像有一两只小动物躲在里面。此外，他还听到蜜蜂的嗡嗡声。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Really, though Trantor……spoken of throughout……Galaxy as an artificial world of metal……ceramic, in this small patch it felt positively rustic. </p><p>真的，纵然整个银河都说川陀是个金属与陶质建成的人工世界，但在这个小小范围内，却令人有置身田园的感觉。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>There were a……other persons taking advantage of……park……wearing light hats, some quite small. There……one rather pretty young woman……far away,……she……bent over a viewer……he could……see……face clearly. A……walked past, looked at……briefly……incuriously, then……down in a seat facing……and buried himself in a sheaf of teleprints, crossing……leg, in……tight pink trouser leg, over……other.</p><p>附近有几个人也在享受这座公园，他们都戴着轻便的帽子，有些相当小。不远处有个挺漂亮的年轻女子，不过她正弯腰凑向一具观景器，他无法看清她的脸庞。此时一名男子经过，对他不经意地望了一眼，然后在对面的椅子上坐下来，埋头阅读一扎电讯报表。那人还翘起二郎腿，谢顿注意到他穿着一条粉红色紧身裤。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>There……a tendency to pastel shades among……men, oddly enough, while……women mostly wore white. Being a clean environment, it made sense to wear light colors. He looked down in amusement at……own Heliconian costume, which……predominantly dull brown. If he were to stay on Trantor as he……not he would need to purchase suitable clothing or he would become an object of curiosity or laughter or repulsion.……man with……teleprints had,……instance, looked up at……more curiously this time……no doubt intrigued by……Outworldish clothing. </p><p>真奇怪，此地男士的衣着倾向于花俏，反倒是女子大多穿着白色衣裳。由于环境相当清洁，穿着淡色服装是很合理的一件事。他低下头来，看了看自己的赫利肯服饰，主要的色系是沉闷的褐色，令他感到有些可笑。假如他要留在川陀……虽说事实不然……就得购买一些适当的衣物，否则必将招来好奇的眼光，或是成为嘲笑或排斥的对象。比方说，那个拿着电讯报表的男子，这回便以较为好奇的眼光抬头望着他，无疑是被他的外星服饰所吸引。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……relieved that he……not smile. He could be philosophical over being a figure of fun, but, surely, he could……be expected to enjoy……</p><p>谢顿庆幸对方并未露出笑容。他对成为笑柄可以处之泰然，不过，当然，他绝不可能会喜欢那种情况。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon watched……man rather unobtrusively,……he seemed to be engaged in some sort of internal debate. At……moment he looked as if he……about to speak, then seemed to think better of……then seemed to wish to speak again. Seldon wondered what……outcome would be.</p><p>谢顿以不着痕迹的方式望着这名男子，因为对方内心似乎在进行一场激战。他看来已经准备开口，然后又好像改变了主意，接下来仿佛又回到原先的决定。谢顿很想知道最后的结果是什么。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He studied……man. He……tall, with broad shoulders……no sign of a paunch, darkish hair with a glint of blond, smooth-shaven, a grave expression, an……of strength though there were no bulging muscles, a face that……a touch rugged……pleasant,……with nothing "pretty" about……</p><p>他仔细打量这名男子。此人个子很高，肩膀宽阔，看不出有任何肚腩，头发是泛着金光的浅黑色，胡子刮得干净，一脸严肃的表情，看来孔武有力，不过并没有盘虬的肌肉，脸庞显得有几分棱角……十分顺眼，但绝对称不上“好看”。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>By……time……man……lost……internal fight with himself……won, perhaps)……leaned toward him, Seldon……decided he liked him. </p><p>等到这名男子内心交战失败了（或者也许是胜利了），将身子倾向谢顿的时候，谢顿认定自己对他已有好感。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The……said, "Pardon……werent……at……Decennial Convention? Mathematics?"</p><p>那人开口道：“对不起，你是不是曾经出席十载会议？那场数学研讨会？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Yes, I was," said Seldon agreeably.</p><p>“是的，我在场。”谢顿欣然答道。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Ah, I thought I……you there. It was……excuse me……that moment of recognition that……me to……here. If I am intruding on your privacy……"</p><p>“啊，我想我在会场见过你。就是因为……对不起……我刚才认出你来，所以才会坐到这里。如果我侵犯了你的隐私……”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Not at all. Im just enjoying an idle moment."</p><p>“一点也没有，我正在享受片刻的悠闲时光。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Lets……how close I……get. Youre Professor Seldon."</p><p>“让我看看还记得多少，你是谢东教授。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Seldon. Hari Seldon. Quite close.……you?"</p><p>“谢顿，哈里·谢顿，不过相当接近了。你呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Chetter Hummin."……man seemed slightly embarrassed. "Rather a homespun name, Im afraid."</p><p>“契特·夫铭，”那人似乎有点尴尬，“只怕是个相当普通的名字。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Ive never come across……Chetters before," said Seldon.……Hummins. So that makes……somewhat unique, I should think. It might be viewed as being better than being mixed up with……the countless Haris there are. Or Seldons,……that matter."</p><p>“我从未碰见过叫契特的人，”谢顿说，“也从不认识姓夫铭的，所以我会认为你相当特别。也许可以这样说，这总比跟数不清的哈里，或是无数的谢顿纠缠不清好得多。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon moved……chair closer to Hummin, scraping it against……slightly elastic ceramoid tiles.</p><p>谢顿将他的椅子挪近夫铭，椅子在带点弹性的陶砖上摩擦出嘎嘎声。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Talk about homespun," he said, "What about this Outworldish clothing Im wearing? It never occurred to me that I ought to……Trantorian garb."</p><p>“谈到普通，”他说，“我这身外星服装怎么样？我压根没想到该弄一套川陀衣饰。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You could……some," said Hummin, eyeing Seldon with suppressed disapproval.</p><p>“你可以去买些。”夫铭一面说，一面以不敢苟同的目光打量谢顿。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Ill be leaving tomorrow and, besides, I couldnt afford……Mathematicians deal with large numbers sometimes,……never in their income.……I presume youre a mathematician, Hummin."</p><p>“我明天就要离开此地，而且我也买不起。数学家有时会处理一些大数目，但绝不是他们的收入……夫铭，我猜你也是个数学家。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"No. Zero talent there."</p><p>“不是，这方面我毫无天分。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Oh." Seldon……disappointed. "You said……saw me at……Decennial Convention."</p><p>“喔。”谢顿有些失望，“你刚才说曾在十载会议上见到我。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I……there as an onlooker. Im a journalist." He waved……teleprints, seemed suddenly aware that he……holding them……shoved them into……jacket pouch. "I supply……material……the news holocasts." Then, thoughtfully, "Actually, Im rather tired of it."</p><p>“我在那里只是旁观，我是个新闻记者。”他挥了挥电讯报表，似乎这才发觉它还在手中，立刻将它塞进外衣口袋。“我为全息新闻供应消息。”然后，他以意味深长的语气说，“其实，我已经相当厌烦。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"The job?"</p><p>“你的工作？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Hummin nodded.……sick of gathering together……the nonsense from every world. I hate……downward spiral."</p><p>夫铭点了点头。“从各个世界收集各种毫无意义的消息，这种差事令我倒胃口。我恨透了每况愈下的世风。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He glanced speculatively at Seldon. "Sometimes something interesting turns……though.……heard……were seen in……company of an Imperial Guard……making……the Palace gate.……werent by……chance seen by……Emperor, were you?" </p><p>他若有所思地瞥了谢顿一眼。“不过，有时还是会发生些有趣的事。我听说有人看到你和一名禁卫军在一起，朝皇宫大门的方向去。你该不会是蒙大帝召见吧？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The smile vanished from Seldons face. He said slowly,……I was, it would scarcely be something I could talk about……publication."</p><p>谢顿脸上的笑容顿时消失无踪，他缓缓说道：“即使真有这回事，也不是我能对新闻界发表的。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"No,……not……publication. If……don't know this, Seldon,……me be……first to tell you……The first rule of……news game is that nothing is ever said about……Emperor or……personal entourage except what is officially given out.……a mistake, of course, because rumors……that……much worse than……truth,……thats……way it is."</p><p>“不，不，不是为了发表。谢顿，如果你不知道这种事，让我第一个告诉你……跑新闻的第一条游戏规则，就是有关皇帝或他身边亲信的消息，除了官方发布的，其他一律不能报道。当然，这样是不对的，因为谣言满天飞远比公布真相要糟得多，可是规则就是这样。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But if……cant report……friend,……do……ask?"</p><p>“但如果不能报道，朋友，你为什么还要问呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Private curiosity. Believe……in my……I know a great deal more than ever gets on……air.……Let me guess. I didnt follow your paper,……I gathered that……were talking about……possibility of predicting……future."</p><p>“私下的好奇心。相信我，干我这一行的，知道的消息比公诸于世的多得多……让我猜猜看：我没有听懂你的论文内容，但我推测你是在谈论预测未来的可能性。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon shook……head……muttered,……was a mistake."</p><p>谢顿摇了摇头，咕哝道：“那是个错误。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Pardon me?"</p><p>“你说什么？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Nothing."</p><p>“没什么。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Well, prediction……accurate prediction……would interest……Emperor, or……man in government, so Im guessing that Cleon, First of that Name, asked……about it……wouldnt……please give……a……predictions."</p><p>“嗯，预测……正确的预测……会令大帝或任何一名政府官员感兴趣。所以我猜克里昂一世曾向你问及这档事，还有你愿不愿意帮他做些预测。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said stiffly, "I don't intend to discuss……matter."</p><p>谢顿以僵硬的语调说：“我不想谈这件事。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Hummin shrugged slightly. "Eto Demerzel……there, I suppose."</p><p>夫铭轻轻耸了耸肩。“我想，伊图·丹莫刺尔也在场吧。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Who?"</p><p>“谁？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Youve never heard of……Demerzel?"</p><p>“你从未听说过伊图·丹莫刺尔？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Never."</p><p>“从来没有。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Cleons alter ego……Cleons brain……Cleons evil spirit.……been called……those things……if we confine ourselves to……nonvituperative. He must have been there."</p><p>“克里昂的另一个自我、克里昂的大脑、克里昂的邪灵……这些都是人们对他的称呼，还不包括那些辱骂性的绰号。他当时一定在场。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon looked confused……Hummin said, "Well,……may……have seen him,……he……there.……if he thinks……can predict……future……"</p><p>谢顿露出困惑的表情。夫铭继续说：“嗯，你也许没看到他，可是他绝对在场。假如他认为你能预测未来……”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I cant predict……future," said Seldon, shaking……head vigorously.……you listened to my paper, youll know that I only spoke of a theoretical possibility."</p><p>“我不能预测未来。”谢顿一面说，一面使劲摇着头，“如果你听过我发表论文，就会知道我只是在谈论理论上的可能性。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Just……same, if he thinks……can predict……future, he will……let……go."</p><p>“没什么不同，假如他认定你能预测未来，他就不会让你走。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"He must have. Here I am."</p><p>“他还是让我走了，现在我才能在这里。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"That means nothing. He knows where……are……hell continue to know.……when he wants you, hell……you, wherever……are.……if he decides youre useful, hell squeeze……use……of you.……if he decides youre dangerous, hell squeeze……life……of you."</p><p>“这点毫无意义。他知道你在哪里，今后会继续掌握你的行踪。当他想要你的时候，不论你在天涯海角，他都能找到你。要是他认为你有用，必定会把你的用处榨干；要是他认为你有威胁性，则会把你的命榨出来。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon stared. "What……you trying to……Frighten me?"</p><p>谢顿瞪着对方。“你想要干什么，吓唬我？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Im trying to warn you."</p><p>“我是想提醒你当心。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I don't believe what youre saying."</p><p>“我不相信你说的这番话。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Dont you? A while……you said something……a mistake. Were……thinking that presenting……paper……a mistake……that it……getting……into……kind of trouble……don't want to be in?"</p><p>“不相信？刚刚你还提到某件事是个错误。你是不是认为发表那篇论文是个错误，因为它给你带来一种避之唯恐不及的麻烦？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……his lower……uneasily. That……a guess that came entirely……close to……truth……and it……at this moment that Seldon felt……presence of intruders.</p><p>谢顿不安地咬着下唇。这个猜测与实情简直太过吻合……就在这个时候，谢顿突然发觉有外人出现。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>They……not cast a shadow,……the light……too soft……widespread. It……simply a movement that caught……corner of……eye……and then it stopped.</p><p>由于光线过度柔和与分散，对方并未投射出任何阴影。只是他的眼角捕捉到一个动作……然后动作便停下来。</p></div>

